BIRTH OF A FAMILY ~

Most new mothers are not inherently distressed or depressed , rather they are depleted from being under resourced and under supported. It’s not because they don’t know how to care for baby, but because their environments are not available to care for them. It may take a village to raise a child, but it also takes a tribe to raise a mother:  and most mothers find themselves….. Tribeless.

The most challenging aspect of early motherhood is not lack of sleep or breastfeeding difficulties but a new mothers’ feelings of loneliness, isolation and a lack of support. We find ourselves mothering in isolation. We are all longing for belonging. The belonging of being a part of a community of other mothers based in mutual support, advice, reassurance, tips and just holding each other close as we go about the daily experience of selflessness required to nurture and nourish our babies.

The indigenous practices that most were forced to abandon are not  just trendy recommendations now, but deeply held traditions rooted in generational indigenous wisdom. Much was lost for many of us in this process as our own ancestors were not allowed to practice their traditions. I say this to remind us that we are all being called to reclaim our traditions, practices, and ancestral women’s wisdom. We were taught to defend our individual rights but not to protect our collective RITES. The rites of passage that honor and celebrate our most significant life experiences through ritual and ceremony. Ceremony was, is and will always be the way we create community. Ceremony creates Community. As we witness and affirm to one another the sacred transitions in life. Motherhood is the great reckoning where we can no longer pretend it is possible to do it all ourselves. Once we realize it is not us as individuals that are failing but societal structures we can go about collectively creating a thriving Post Partum Culture, with the recognition that Mothering is Communal. 
With love , GENEVIEVE

THROUGH OUR WOMBS WE CONNECT TO OUR HUMANITY ~ WHICH BECOMES A COLLECTIVE CALL TO ACT MORE HUMANELY ~ 
What does it mean to embrace WOMB HEALING? It means to deconstruct, question and change everything that we have been taught and programmed to believe until now. So many of us are feeling deep grief and the heavy burden of an increasingly broken society.  We were raised and programmed to value independence, self-sufficiency, autonomy and self-reliance. We believed as children in being praised  doing things ‘ by ourself ‘. We have ‘parentified’ babies resulting in attempts to teach even newborns  how to toilet train and sleep all night.  We value  self-mastery, progress and improvement so even breastfeeding our babies to sleep is seen as being a ‘crutch’  and baby wearing and co-sleeping as  creating dependence and thwarting progression. If we as a society increasingly see even a small baby’s needs as problematic how will new mothers feel safe enough to express their needs and ask for help. Is it any surprise that so many of us have painful periods and suffer emotionally and physically during our menstrual cycle because we are not able to openly respond to our needs for increased sleep and rest. Through birth, menstruation,  pregnancy , post partum and menopause we rely heavily on the industrial medical complex to meet our needs but overlook the fact that they are experts in pathology not health and motivated equally by profit as well as improving health But it is during the last stage of life, our entry into our 60’s , 70’s, and 80’s when rather than  being encouraged to embrace our role as a wise elder and grandmother we become even more invisible and are expected to hide our frailty,  diminishment and even our dying. What I see is a society that refuses to accept our humanity, our needs, our limits, and then has no idea how to create structures to better resource us all.  In  connecting to our wombs we connect to our needs. Creating community is our immunity. We  can begin to embrace our wombs as the sovereign and sacred places that they are. We can enjoy the sensual discovery of being human and the gift of our bodies as a living compass, with love Genevieve

☽ EL PARTO ES UN ACTO SEXUAL ⟁ 
Me estáis preguntando muchísimo por mi parto, cómo ha sido y que por qué en casa. Cuando supimos que estábamos embarazados era lo único que teníamos claro, queríamos ocuparnos de manera consciente del nacimiento de nuestra hija y no medicalizarlo sin necesidad. (Afortunadamente , así ha sido.)
Parir duele, si, pero también es un viaje increíble en el que conectas con la sexualidad más profunda de tu ser. Sale lo más instintivo y animal que hay en ti, y te “partes” de manera literal para ser el canal de una nueva vida. Morir para volver a renacer más empoderada y conectada contigo misma. 
.
El viaje no ha sido solo mío, también de @jaferreirag quien me ha sostenido en cada momento y ha ido sabiendo cómo bailar las olas, que a veces eran suaves y terminaron siendo salvajes y muy intensas. Un trabajo en equipo junto a Danae, que también sabía cómo hacerlo. 
.
Obviamente había personas expertas en traer bebés al mundo de manera respetada, humana y consciente. Como gatas, observaban desde una esquina, actuando cuando se requirió y dejándonos ser, estar, y hacer. 
.
El cuerpo sabe parir. No hay que desgarrarse y empujar sin sentido. 
El bebé sabe nacer. Solo hay que acompañarle, hablarle y confiar. 
.
El parto comenzó bailando, lleno de caricias y besos, de fotos, de olores ricos de mis aceites esenciales, huesos de dátiles para generar endorfinas y de risas y bromas. Cómo dice la matrona empieza “en el aire”. (Aún tienes el control) Cuando dilatas más o menos 7cm todo cambia, y llega “el agua”lágrimas, limpieza, e incluso desesperación. Hay que seguir. 
La piscina fue una manera de diluirme en el momento, el columpio me ayudó a estirarme entera y columpiarme en cada contracción. 
.
“El aro de fuego” anunciaba que Danae estaba cerca, e invitaba a seguir dejando que las olas hicieran su función , ¡pero que dolor! La intensidad más fuerte que mI cuerpo ha experimentado. Ya iban casi 15 horas y Danae asomó la cabecita. Ha sido la sensación más extraña e increíble que he sentido jamas. Ellas me asistieron y mi amor no me soltó ni un segundo. BREATH OF LIFE 

✨The First Breath✨Babies are born with fluid-filled lungs. 🫁 

In the birth process, the intense pressure from the birth canal squeezes and expels the fluid from baby’s lungs, which you can see in this video! 👀

Before they can breathe air, the fluid must be expelled or absorbed into their body.💧

When a baby is born, they go though a rapid physiological process to become air-breathers. The first two or three breaths help their lung capillaries expand and absorb the water which is dispersed into their organs. The next few breaths help the lungs inflate with air. 🌬

You may hear your baby cough or discharge fluid as they are clearing the fluid from their lungs- this is entirely normal and physiological.

🔁 The change in pressure- from a tight birth canal to a air-filled room- creates a vacuum that helps their body absorb the water AND pulls blood from the placenta. A bolus of blood is backed up into the placenta due to the compression of the baby, which then drains back into baby immediately after birth. 🩸 

Don’t cut the cord early! That blood is baby’s blood and it provides up to 1/3 their entire blood volume. ✂️ 

All of these changes happen so quickly after birth, you might miss it!

❓Isn’t it incredible how the female body is perfectly designed for birth?

There is no SELF CARE  during POST PARTUM .. 

the reason there isn’t Self Care during early mamahood is because even if we let go of, scale back , or shorten our most loved Self Care practices that we had before becoming mothers .. whether that was a yoga class, body massage , or even a glass of wine …..these same practices are almost impossible as a new mama without another human being involved to care for baby as we try to self care for ourselves

In this way our Self Care becomes Community Care .. a long hot shower or bath is possible if our partner or another adult can care for baby while we try to replenish ourselves and take actions that will leave us feeling less depleted ..

WE MOURN ~ the loss of legendary leader Haunani K. Trask. She was the sharp tip of a spear in a movement that fought for our people, helping us march toward a better understanding of where we came from - historically and politically. 

Haunani fearlessly advocated for our people by speaking truth to power, and she did not waiver in saying out loud the actual history that so many have tried to make us forget. She inspired a generation of Hawaiians to not only learn our history but to engage at every level with the truth from a new and grounded perspective on where we need to go next as a community. Those conversations were never easy,  and those ideas were never popular in the mainstream. And yet now, a generation later, we can see that Hawai’i is different because of her.
